{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643995"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:00:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:00:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18029"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18029"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73416"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10743"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18029"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58885"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1132"},{"type":"tags","id":"1194"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25065"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25121"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73416"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number imaging modalities which can be used to assessing skull fractures (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the gold standard for detecting a skull fracture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT scan","PET","Plain X-ray","MRI","Ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for detecting skull fractures due to its high sensitivity and ability to provide detailed images of bone structures. It is the preferred imaging modality in the acute setting, especially in cases of head trauma, as it can quickly identify fractures and any associated intracranial injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E plain X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is less sensitive than CT for detecting skull fractures and may miss subtle fractures. It is not typically used in the acute setting for head trauma due to its limitations in sensitivity and specificity. It might be used if CT imaging facilities were not available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used for detecting skull fractures as it is better suited for soft tissue evaluation, such as brain parenchyma, and is not as effective in visualising bone structures compared to CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not used for detecting skull fractures as it is not effective in visualising bone structures. It is more commonly used for soft tissue evaluation and in specific settings such as paediatrics for assessing fontanelles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET\u003C/strong\u003E is not used for detecting skull fractures. It is a functional imaging modality used to assess metabolic activity and is not suitable for evaluating bone integrity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT scan is the gold standard for detecting skull fractures due to its high sensitivity and ability to provide detailed images of bone structures.","X-ray is less sensitive than CT for detecting skull fractures and may miss subtle fractures.","MRI is not typically used for detecting skull fractures as it is better suited for soft tissue evaluation."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58885"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18029"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21357"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21357"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9h2IjB76BEUV2vA1ABGXT0dk1dCVuw.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9h2IjB76BEUV2vA1ABGXT0dk1dCVuw.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":536,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58885"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T19:54:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T19:55:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10743"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73416"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"sel